-- Japan, Indonesia, Thailand, Philippines: Asian Bond and Currency Preview
-- Anil Varma
-- 2010-06-14T22:45:05Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-14/japan-indonesia-thailand-philippines-asian-bond-and-currency-preview.html

          
          
             The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise. Financial
markets in China are closed for the first three trading days of
this week and those in the Philippines were shut yesterday for
holidays.  
 Japan: The Bank of Japan today will keep the benchmark
interest rate at 0.1 percent at the end of a two-day policy
meeting, according to all 14 economists in a Bloomberg News
survey.  
 Chief Cabinet Secretary Yoshito Sengoku will hold a media
briefing at 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  
 The yield on the 1.3 percent government bond due June 2020
was 1.23 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest inter-dealer debt broker.  
 The yen traded at 91.63 per dollar at 7:35 a.m. in Tokyo.  
 India: The government plans to raise as much as 30 billion
rupees ($644 million) selling treasury bills at an auction
tomorrow. It will offer 20 billion rupees of 91-day securities
and 10 billion rupees of 364-day notes.  
 The yield on the 7.8 percent bond due May 2020 was 7.69
percent. The rupee was at 46.49.  
 Indonesia: The government will sell Islamic debt maturing
in five years and 10 years today.  
 The yield on the 11 percent bond due November 2020 was at
8.65 percent, according to Inter Dealer Market Association. The
rupiah was at 9,170 per dollar.  
 Thailand: The central bank will sell 18 billion baht ($555
million) of 28-day bills, 15 billion baht of 91-day notes and
12 billion baht of 182-day securities. The bank will also issue
40 billion baht of 364-day bills and 30 billion baht of two-
year bonds.  
 The yield on the 3.875 percent bond maturing in June 2019
was 3.25 percent. The baht was at 32.40.  
 Malaysia: The central bank plans to auction a combined 3
billion ringgit ($918 million) in 91- and 210-day debt tomorrow.
In addition, the bank will also sell 500 million ringgit of 89-
day Islamic notes.  
 The yield on the 4.378 percent note due November 2019 was
4.08 percent. The ringgit was at 3.2520 today.  
 Singapore: The government will tomorrow report retail
sales data for April and economists surveyed by Bloomberg are
forecasting a 0.8 percent increase from a year earlier,
following a 2.4 percent slide in March.  
 The yield on the 3.25 percent notes due September 2020 was
2.63 percent. The Singapore dollar was at S$1.3969.  
 Philippines: The government plans to auction 1.5 billion
pesos ($32 million) of 91-day bills and 3 billion pesos of 182-
day securities today. It will also offer 3.5 billion pesos of
364-day notes.  
 The peso was at 46.438.  
